al_logic\";i:0;s:7:\"wrapper\";a:3:{s:5:\"width\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"class\";s:0:\"\";s:2:\"id\";s:0:\"\";}s:9:\"post_type\";a:1:{i:0;s:4:\"post\";}s:8:\"taxonomy\";s:0:\"\";s:10:\"allow_null\";i:0;s:8:\"multiple\";i:0;s:13:\"return_format\";s:2:\"id\";s:2:\"ui\";i:1;}','Post 3','section_d__blog_c','publish','closed','closed','','field_5d0d8120fab8f','','','2019-06-26 05:40:30','2019-06-26 05:40:30','',22,'http://bmcoblog.wpengine.com/?post_type=acf-field&#038;p=25',2,'acf-field','',0),(26,1,'2019-06-22 01:15:59','2019-06-22 01:15:59','a:11:{s:4:\"type\";s:11:\"post_object\";s:12:\"instructions\";s:0:\"\";s:8:\"required\";i:1;s:17:\"conditional_logic\";i:0;s:7:\"wrapper\";a:3:{s:5:\"width\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"class\";s:0:\"\";s:2:\"id\";s:0:\"\";}s:9:\"post_type\";a:1:{i:0;s:4:\"post\";}s:8:\"taxonomy\";s:0:\"\";s:10:\"allow_null\";i:0;s:8:\"multiple\";i:0;s:13:\"return_format\";s:2:\"id\";s:2:\"ui\";i:1;}','Post 4','section_d__blog_d','publish','closed','closed','','field_5d0d813cfab90','','','2019-06-26 05:40:30','2019-06-26 05:40:30','',22,'http://bmcoblog.wpengine.com/?post_type=acf-field&#038;p=26',3,'acf-field','',0),(1633,8,'2019-12-17 18:29:10','2019-12-17 18:29:10','<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":50} -->\n<div style=\"height:50px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Go outside your comfort zone, challenge yourself, do something new, see the world — and stay safe, with these ten travel tips from explorer J.J. Kelley.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>1. Always Tell A Friend (Maybe Even Two or Three)</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I would say most of the disappearances we’ve investigated could have been prevented by letting a friend know where you’re going and when you’ll be back. Pick a trustworthy and reliable loved one who can be held accountable to check on you if you don’t surface at the designated time. <br><br>Every moment you’re lost in the wild is crucial, and the first 48 hours are the most important. After two days in the wild, your chances of survival drop significantly. So tell a friend — better yet, tell 2 or 3 friends — where you’re going (be specific) and when you’ll be back. If they don’t hear from you, then they should call the local authorities and your country\'s embassy. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>2. Download a Scan of Your Passport on your Phone&nbsp;</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It’s a good idea to have printed copies of the two front pages of your passport and any visas or immigration stamps for that country. Short of printed copies, always have these photos downloaded on your phone. <br><br>I’ve seen it happen dozens of times, people are overpowered by the elements and their bag is lost, or you’re jet-lagged and don’t notice you forgot a bag in the taxi. Your passport is vital for international travel; without one you’re helpless. Having the scan can get you through tight situations while you make your way to your nearest embassy for help. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>3. Always Carry Basic Survival Gear</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I’d estimate 90% of our disappearance cases involve people who are underprepared. Surprisingly, smaller excursions can be the most dangerous. Think about it, if you’re going on a multi-day trip you’ll have food, water, and shelter. However, it’s those 3-hour tours that can turn deadly. The conditions might look perfect when you set out at 11 AM, but imagine what it will be like at night if you don’t make it back. Imagine how you’d feel if it starts to pour, or&nbsp;worse yet, snow. What if the temps drop by 20 degrees? <br><br>Now I’m not saying you need to bring a loaded down backpack on your next day-hike, but having just a few simple items could save your life. I recommend an Emergency Blanket, a headlamp, 2-liters of water, an extra layer, two energy bars, a battery to recharge your phone, and a compass. It might feel like overkill, but I promise you, if many of our subjects had had these necessities they’d still be here today. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>4. Worst Case, Shelter In Place&nbsp;</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Many of us can relate to the sun going down as we panic, hoping to make it back to civilization in time. It’s a horrifying feeling to be racing the sun. When it happens, our adrenalin starts surging and we’re more likely to make mistakes. <br><br>When you’re lost, slow down! Sit down and slow your breath; think about where you are and your choices. If you followed Tip #3, you should have a few survival items to get you through what promises to be an uncomfortable night, but you will survive. It’s when you wander through the woods at night that you’re more likely to have a serious accident —so worst case, shelter in place. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>5. Don’t Be Too Trustworthy&nbsp;</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, I don’t want to inspire paranoid travelers, but when moving about the world a healthy bit of skepticism isn’t the worst outlook to have. In fact, it could save your life. Often times when we travel we’re looking for a transcendent experience — we become more vulnerable. We put ourselves out there more than we would in our everyday lives. <br><br>This can open you up to new experiences, but if you go too far, it can be deadly. For example, if someone in your hometown asked you to get in their van to go check out a holy cave where you can meditate, you’d be like no way weirdo! However, if you’re in India and a guru who looks the part asks you to join him in meditation, you might be more likely to say, why not, when will I ever get this chance again. <br><br>The majority of people in the world are&nbsp;good, but I’ve seen foreigners targeted by scammers more times than I’d like to admit. If it doesn’t feel right in your gut, don’t do it! </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>6. Have Communication Sorted Before You Fly&nbsp;</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cell phone connectivity worldwide has come a long way over the last 10 years. Gone are the days when using your cellphone for a call or data would cost you a small fortune. With a little planning, you might be able to use your phone for $5 or less a day. <br><br>Another strategy is to get a local Sim Card, but I don’t love this because if you call a friend for help your number will show up as a random foreign line that could be avoided because it looks like SPAM. A cell phone isn’t guaranteed to save your life, but your chances improve tremendously with one in your pocket if things turn south. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>7. Smile&nbsp;</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Unless it’s culturally inappropriate — you can ask your taxi driver on your way from the airport if you’re not sure — smile. Being friendly and greeting strangers with a kind gesture shows people you’re not a threat. When you’re alone or in a small group, it’s always better to have friends on your side. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>8. Explore the Cuisine&nbsp;</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>OK, we’re kind of walking the razor\'s edge a little here, but I’m encouraging you to take advantage of the world’s rich flavors. Nothing bums me out more than being with travelers who’d rather eat at McDonald\'s or the hotel than try the local hotspot. I’m the kind of guy who eats my way through countries, and I’ve been exposed to the most extraordinary culinary delights. After 111 countries visited, I’ve for sure had my share of stomach bugs, but it’s never been anything a little Cypro or Azithromycin couldn’t clear up. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>9. Find Your Travel Doctor&nbsp;</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I love geeking out about a destination with my travel doctor. I tell her everything, what the temperatures will be, what times of day I’ll be outside, the kind of environment I’ll be in, and what regions of the country I’ll see. Be specific and take their advice. I’ve been&nbsp;poked with needles more times than I can count, but I’ve been lucky to never catch anything deadly. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>10. Don’t Get Caught In A Routine&nbsp;</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It’s a good strategy for life in general, but it could be lifesaving overseas. If you’re staying in a town for more than a few days, it can be fun to settle into a routine. As someone who spends 60% of my life traveling, I miss routine. <br><br>However, you don’t want to make a habit of going to a specific spot at the same time traveling the same route every day. When you’re in another country, chances are you’ll stand out, and if someone sketchy notices you walking the same path every day at the same time then it makes targeting you very easy. Mix things up and always stay one step ahead of any scam artists or thugs. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><a href=\"http://www.jjkelley.com/\"><strong>J.J. Kelley</strong></a><strong>&nbsp;is an Emmy-nominated filmmaker, producer, director, and explorer</strong> focused conservation issues and wildlife crime. An avid adventurer and fellow at the Explorers Club, Kelley brings a unique mix of humor and grit to his subjects — his new show, <em><a href=\"https://www.travelchannel.com/shows/lost-in-the-wild\">Lost in the Wild</a></em>, premieres December 29th. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":50} -->\n<div style=\"height:50px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->','10 Travel and Wilderness Tips','','publish','open','open','','10-travel-and-wilderness-tips','','','2019-12-17 18:40:15','2019-12-17 18:40:15','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?p=1633',0,'post','',0),(1678,8,'2019-12-27 02:33:59','2019-12-27 02:33:59','<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":35} -->\n<div style=\"height:35px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>James Beard Award-winning chefs Vinny Dotolo and Jon Shook share their recipe for basic crêpes, along with two of their favorite variations on the French classic. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":30} -->\n<div style=\"height:30px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Basic Crêpes</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Makes 10 Crêpes</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Ingredients</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>1 cup whole milk&nbsp;</li><li>3 large eggs&nbsp;</li><li>1 tbsp vegetable oil, plus extra as needed&nbsp;</li><li>1⁄2 cup all-purpose flour&nbsp;</li><li>Jam or Nutella spread </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Directions</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>Whisk 1⁄2 cup of the milk, the eggs, and 1 tablespoon of oil together in a large bowl. Add the flour and whisk until smooth, then whisk in the remaining 1⁄2 cup milk. Cover with plastic wrap and refrigerate for 1 hour or up to 2 days. <br><br></li><li>Brush your cast iron skillet with a little oil and set it over medium-high heat for 1 minute. Ladle about 1⁄4 cup of batter into the skillet. Swirl the skillet to coat the pan bottom evenly and cook the batter until golden brown, 30 to 60 seconds, adjusting the heat as needed so the crêpe doesn’t get too dark. <br><br></li><li>Run a heat-proof silicone rubber spatula around the edges of the crêpe to release it from the skillet, then flip the crêpe over and brown the other side. Transfer the cooked crêpe to a plate and repeat with the remaining batter. <br><br></li><li>Spread with jam or Nutella and roll to serve. </li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":35} -->\n<div style=\"height:35px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also try...</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":35} -->\n<div style=\"height:35px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Flaming Crêpes Suzette</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Ingredients</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>1 batch Basic Crêpe batter (above)</li><li>2 oranges</li><li>1/4 cup sugar</li><li>1/4 cup Grand Marnier or Cointreau</li><li>2 tbsp unsalted butter</li><li>Vanilla ice cream</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Directions&nbsp;</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>Make one batch of Basic Crêpe batter, cook the crêpes, fold each one into quarters, and set aside. <br><br></li><li>Using the small holes of a box grater or a citrus zester, remove the zest from the oranges (just the zest, not the bitter white pith) and juice them to get 1⁄2 cup juice. <br><br></li><li>Bring the orange juice and sugar to a simmer in a large skillet over medium-high heat. Once the sugar is dissolved, add the Grand Marnier or Cointreau, and using a long wooden match, ignite the sauce (don’t keep the open bottle of alcohol near the stove).<br><br></li><li>Let the alcohol burn off, then add the zest and unsalted butter. Once the butter melts, add the folded crêpes to the skillet and turn over in the sauce to coat well. <br><br></li><li>Serve topped with a scoop of vanilla ice cream. </li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":50} -->\n<div style=\"height:50px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Ham and Swiss Crêpes</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Ingredients</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>1 batch Basic Crêpe batter (above)</li><li>8 oz Gruyère cheese</li><li>10 slices of ham</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Directions</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>Make one batch of crêpe batter. While the batter rests, grate the Gruyère cheese (about 2 1⁄2 cups) and set aside. <br><br></li><li>Place 10 slices of ham next to your cooktop. Cook the crêpes as described above. <br><br></li><li>After flipping each crêpe, sprinkle the cooked side with 1⁄4 cup of the cheese and add 1 slice of the ham. <br><br></li><li>Fold into thirds (like a business letter) and serve. </li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":30} -->\n<div style=\"height:30px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Jon Shook</strong> and <strong>Vinny Dotolo</strong> are James Beard Award-winning icons of the Los Angeles food world. The pair worked together at The Strange, Mark\'s, Café Maxx, The River House, and Wildflower Restaurant before making the move to L.A. in 2001. After launching their own catering company, they opened their restaurant Animal in 2008. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":50} -->\n<div style=\"height:50px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->','Crêpes, Three Ways','','publish','open','open','','crepes-three-ways','','','2019-12-27 02:34:03','2019-12-27 02:34:03','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?p=1678',0,'post','',0),(1679,8,'2019-12-19 20:46:14','2019-12-19 20:46:14','','Crepes Feature','','inherit','open','closed','','crepes-feature','','','2019-12-19 20:46:14','2019-12-19 20:46:14','',1678,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Crepes-Feature.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1680,8,'2019-12-19 20:48:23','2019-12-19 20:48:23','','Crepes Thumbnail','','inherit','open','closed','','crepes-thumbnail','','','2019-12-19 20:48:23','2019-12-19 20:48:23','',1678,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Crepes-Thumbnail.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(290,2,'2019-07-22 03:26:53','2019-07-22 03:26:53','<iframe title=\"Best Made Co First Aid Kit (Small)\" width=\"500\" height=\"281\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/azhgpmxFp4w?start=2&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen></iframe>','','','publish','closed','closed','','86ea222b89bf08d1c6562a48d4a6c7ff','','','2019-07-22 03:26:53','2019-07-22 03:26:53','',0,'https://b