losed','','the-leather-pot-handle','','','2019-11-06 15:56:31','2019-11-06 15:56:31','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?post_type=product&#038;p=776',0,'product','',0),(777,8,'2019-11-06 15:56:22','2019-11-06 15:56:22','','PotHandle','','inherit','open','closed','','pothandle','','','2019-11-06 15:56:22','2019-11-06 15:56:22','',776,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/PotHandle.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1304,8,'2019-11-14 20:58:28','2019-11-14 20:58:28','','Japan Craft 11','\"Being able to read grains will change how you see trees, and changing how you see trees can make you see nature differently.” — Masaru Kawai','inherit','open','closed','','japan-craft-11','','','2019-11-14 21:05:37','2019-11-14 21:05:37','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Japan-Craft-11.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1516,8,'2019-12-03 17:48:10','2019-12-03 17:48:10','','Bavaria_Woodshifter5','','inherit','open','closed','','bavaria_woodshifter5','','','2019-12-03 17:48:10','2019-12-03 17:48:10','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Bavaria_Woodshifter5.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1306,8,'2019-11-14 20:58:32','2019-11-14 20:58:32','','Japan Craft 13','','inherit','open','closed','','japan-craft-13','','','2019-11-14 20:58:32','2019-11-14 20:58:32','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Japan-Craft-13.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1305,8,'2019-11-14 20:58:30','2019-11-14 20:58:30','','Japan Craft 12','','inherit','open','closed','','japan-craft-12','','','2019-11-14 20:58:30','2019-11-14 20:58:30','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Japan-Craft-12.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1688,8,'2020-01-06 15:26:12','2020-01-06 15:26:12','','The Best Made Leather Key Fob','','publish','closed','closed','','the-best-made-leather-key-fob','','','2020-01-06 15:26:12','2020-01-06 15:26:12','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?post_type=product&#038;p=1688',0,'product','',0),(1647,8,'2019-12-13 17:48:33','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":35} -->\n<div style=\"height:35px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My grandma moved from Japan to South Carolina in the 50s after marrying my American grandpa. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With scant available Japanese ingredients, she got crafty in making meals for her family using what she had access to, while still holding on to Japanese culinary tradition; she always made fried rice in a cast iron pan, and almost always with peas and carrots and plenty of soy sauce (for which she would write monthly letters and send money to Katagiri Market in New York City). </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can add any vegetables you wish or even meat, but it helps if they\'re fully cooked first. The rice MUST be cold, as hot fresh rice will make a gummy mess. This makes it the perfect throw-all-the-leftovers-into-a-pan-I-have-no-time-to-cook kind of meal.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":30} -->\n<div style=\"height:30px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Fried Rice</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Serves 2<br></h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Ingredients</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>3 tbsp neutral oil, like grapeseed or canola</li><li>4 cups cooked white rice, cold (I use Kokuho Rose, a medium grain <em>japonica</em> variety from Koda Farms in California)</li><li>3 tbsp soy sauce or tamari</li><li>2 cups cooked vegetables and/or meat (I like spring peas and broccoli rabe)</li><li>2 eggs, whisked with a pinch of salt added</li><li>2 scallions, sliced thinly</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Directions</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>Get a cast iron pan hot over medium-high heat.<br></li><li>Add oil, which should be hot enough that it moves freely and shimmers, and perhaps begins to smoke a little.<br></li><li>Add rice to the pan, keeping some largish clumps intact.<br></li><li>Turn heat down to medium, and stir and turn rice with a large flat metal spatula for about a minute or two — the rice will crisp a little, but not much.<br></li><li>Add soy sauce and quickly stir to distribute; the soy sauce will caramelize and crisp the rice.<br></li><li>Leave the rice to crisp on the bottom for a couple of minutes, then turn, in large chunks, to crisp another side. Repeat this once more.&nbsp;<br></li><li>Add vegetables, and stir.<br></li><li>Move the rice to the edges to make a hole in the middle of the pan.<br></li><li>Add egg, and stir quickly as it cooks; don\'t worry if some rice gets mixed into the egg.<br></li><li>Once cooked, distribute the egg, add scallion, and check for salt (my mom always adds black pepper here, but I don\'t).<br></li><li>Add scallions and serve immediately — top with furikake, hot sauce, or whatever else you\'d like. </li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Patch Troffer </strong>is the Executive Chef at Marlow &amp; Sons restaurant in Williamsburg, New York. Troffer\'s previous work includes stints at Bar Tartine and Camino in the Bay Area.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":50} -->\n<div style=\"height:50px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->','Grammy Yukie\'s Cast Iron Fried Rice','','draft','open','open','','','','','2019-12-13 17:48:33','2019-12-13 17:48:33','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?p=1647',0,'post','',0),(1651,8,'2019-12-13 15:37:42','2019-12-13 15:37:42','','Ice Fishing 1','','inherit','open','closed','','ice-fishing-1','','','2019-12-13 15:37:42','2019-12-13 15:37:42','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Ice-Fishing-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1652,8,'2019-12-13 15:37:44','2019-12-13 15:37:44','','Ice Fishing 2','','inherit','open','closed','','ice-fishing-2','','','2019-12-13 15:37:44','2019-12-13 15:37:44','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Ice-Fishing-2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1653,8,'2019-12-13 15:37:47','2019-12-13 15:37:47','','Ice Fishing 3','','inherit','open','closed','','ice-fishing-3','','','2019-12-13 15:37:47','2019-12-13 15:37:47','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Ice-Fishing-3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1654,8,'2019-12-13 15:37:49','2019-12-13 15:37:49','','Ice Fishing 4','','inherit','open','closed','','ice-fishing-4','','','2019-12-13 15:37:49','2019-12-13 15:37:49','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Ice-Fishing-4.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1655,8,'2019-12-13 15:37:51','2019-12-13 15:37:51','','Ice Fishing 5','','inherit','open','closed','','ice-fishing-5','','','2019-12-13 15:37:51','2019-12-13 15:37:51','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Ice-Fishing-5.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1656,8,'2019-12-13 15:37:52','2019-12-13 15:37:52','','Ice Fishing 6','','inherit','open','closed','','ice-fish