918,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/6Strongbox.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(920,8,'2019-11-07 18:52:09','2019-11-07 18:52:09','','The 6\" Multicolored Strongbox','','publish','closed','closed','','the-6-multicolored-strongbox','','','2019-11-07 18:52:09','2019-11-07 18:52:09','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?post_type=product&#038;p=920',0,'product','',0),(921,8,'2019-11-07 18:52:00','2019-11-07 18:52:00','','6MulticoloredStrongbox','','inherit','open','closed','','6multicoloredstrongbox','','','2019-11-07 18:52:00','2019-11-07 18:52:00','',920,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/6MulticoloredStrongbox.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(922,8,'2019-11-07 18:52:37','2019-11-07 18:52:37','','The Pocket Strongbox','','publish','closed','closed','','the-pocket-strongbox','','','2019-11-07 18:52:37','2019-11-07 18:52:37','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?post_type=product&#038;p=922',0,'product','',0),(923,8,'2019-11-07 18:52:28','2019-11-07 18:52:28','','PocketStrongbox','','inherit','open','closed','','pocketstrongbox','','','2019-11-07 18:52:28','2019-11-07 18:52:28','',922,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/PocketStrongbox.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(989,8,'2019-11-07 21:42:35','2019-11-07 21:42:35','','Slider 900 - image','','publish','closed','closed','','slider-900-image-3','','','2019-11-07 21:56:28','2019-11-07 21:56:28','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?post_type=ml-slide&#038;p=989',2,'ml-slide','',0),(931,8,'2019-08-24 19:50:00','2019-08-24 19:50:00','<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a Boy Scout, I was required to learn a good handful of knots. Some, like the Square Knot or the Sheepshank, are so simple that I’ve never been able to forget them, despite how rarely I use them. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Others are so complex I question how I ever learned to tie them at all, such as the Turk’s Head and Carrick Bend; these knots are mostly decorative, and I forgot how to tie them many years ago. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is, however, a small group of knots that I’ve never forgotten, because they are so helpful around the house and in the field. The following three knots are those that I’ve been tying on a consistent basis for many years. &nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator {\"className\":\"is-style-dots\"} -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator is-style-dots\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<h3 style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>Taut-Line Hitch: For When Tight is Right</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is by far my most used knot. As a slipping knot, it makes adjusting a length of rope easy but provides enough friction to resist loosening. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Taut-line is my go-to for staking out tent and rain flys or setting up a simple clothesline. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Anytime you need a knot that will allow you to tighten the tension of a rope between two points, the Taut-Line is almost always the answer.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":30} -->\n<div style=\"height:30px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<h3 style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>Bowline: For Safety and Security</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are a select few knots, like the Bowline and its variations, strong enough to be used in critical applications. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It’s most commonly learned with the \"rabbit and the hole\" process, and I’ve often shamelessly repeated this little story when tying one: The rabbit comes out of his hole. The rabbit runs around the tree. The rabbit runs back down his hole. The rabbit stops to watch the tree grow.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Bowline knot tightens under pressure but relaxes when that pressure is released, making it easy to untie. It’s often used in nautical, and rescue applications — I employ it on safety ropes when canoeing.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":30} -->\n<div style=\"height:30px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<h3 style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>Surgeon’s Loop: for Speed and Ease</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For times when the reliability of a Bowline is not needed, the simple Surgeon’s Loop shines. It\'s dead simple, quick to tie, and reliable enough for light applications. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This knot will tighten under pressure and can be difficult to untie, especially when wet. I often use a Surgeon’s Loop in conjunction with the Taut-Line in a modified Trucker Hitch, which is great for high tension applications or when compression is needed, such as around a bundle of firewood. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a bonus knot, if you add an additional twist to the initial step you\'ll get a Figure-8-Follow-Thru — this variation adds strength, and is commonly used by rock climbers on safety harnesses.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator {\"className\":\"is-style-dots\"} -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator is-style-dots\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Even after all these years, I still find novel uses for all three of these knots. Using a Bowline to tie a lost dog to a telephone pole while I looked for his owner. Tying the driver-side door shut on my old Buick one winter, when it got so cold the lock froze open. Tying the bumper back onto a rental car after a friend ripped it off by catching it on a tree branch in the Catskills.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Regardless of what knots you’re tying, you\'ll need rope, so always pack enough. 50 feet of 3/8 inch polypropylene for the car, 25 feet of 550 paracord for your backpack, and a 100-foot spool of 1/16 inch microcord is more than enough rope to get the job done — no matter what scenario you find yourself in.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":50} -->\n<div style=\"height:50px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->','Three Knots Everyone Should Know','','publish','open','open','','three-knots-everyone-should-know','','','2019-11-14 22:18:29','2019-11-14 22:18:29','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?p=931',0,'post','',0),(932,8,'2019-11-07 19:46:51','2019-11-07 19:46:51','','BMCO_