'',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/The-Good-Fight-18.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1340,8,'2019-11-14 21:49:18','2019-11-14 21:49:18','','The Good Fight 19','','inherit','open','closed','','the-good-fight-19','','','2019-11-14 21:49:18','2019-11-14 21:49:18','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/The-Good-Fight-19.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1341,8,'2019-11-14 21:49:19','2019-11-14 21:49:19','','The Good Fight 20','','inherit','open','closed','','the-good-fight-20','','','2019-11-14 21:49:19','2019-11-14 21:49:19','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/The-Good-Fight-20.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1342,8,'2019-11-14 21:49:19','2019-11-14 21:49:19','','The Good Fight 21','','inherit','open','closed','','the-good-fight-21','','','2019-11-14 21:49:19','2019-11-14 21:49:19','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/The-Good-Fight-21.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1343,8,'2019-11-14 21:49:20','2019-11-14 21:49:20','','The Good Fight Thumbnail','','inherit','open','closed','','the-good-fight-thumbnail','','','2019-11-14 21:56:53','2019-11-14 21:56:53','',493,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/The-Good-Fight-Thumbnail.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1344,8,'2019-11-14 21:51:46','2019-11-14 21:51:46','','Svalbard 1A','','publish','closed','closed','','new-slideshow-14','','','2019-11-14 21:52:19','2019-11-14 21:52:19','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?post_type=ml-slider&#038;p=1344',0,'ml-slider','',0),(1345,8,'2019-11-14 21:52:01','2019-11-14 21:52:01','','Slider 1344 - image','','publish','closed','closed','','slider-1344-image','','','2019-11-14 21:52:19','2019-11-14 21:52:19','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?post_type=ml-slide&#038;p=1345',0,'ml-slide','',0),(1346,8,'2019-11-14 21:52:09','2019-11-14 21:52:09','','Slider 1344 - image','','publish','closed','closed','','slider-1344-image-2','','','2019-11-14 21:52:19','2019-11-14 21:52:19','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?post_type=ml-slide&#038;p=1346',1,'ml-slide','',0),(1347,8,'2019-11-14 21:52:16','2019-11-14 21:52:16','','Slider 1344 - image','','publish','closed','closed','','slider-1344-image-3','','','2019-11-14 21:52:19','2019-11-14 21:52:19','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?post_type=ml-slide&#038;p=1347',2,'ml-slide','',0),(935,8,'2019-06-07 20:06:51','2019-06-07 20:06:51','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I often heard the phrase “Come over here and let me show you how an anchor works,” from my father as we sat fishing in the little aluminum rowboat that used to be Uncle Stan’s. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It was his usual response when I would question the size of the fish he’d just caught or challenge the \"truthiness\" of one of his many stories. He always said it jokingly, implying that he would like to throw me overboard. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Still, it made me wonder exactly what <em>was</em> happening down there, as I watched our little mushroom anchor disappear into the murky lake water.&nbsp;I imagined the anchor dropping straight down to the lake bottom, with its weight holding us securely in place —&nbsp;but when I would go fishing by myself, drop the anchor, and expect it to work, I always found myself drifting.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1200,\"align\":\"center\",\"width\":768,\"height\":389} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter is-resized\"><img src=\"http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Anchor-Illustration-1024x518.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1200\" width=\"768\" height=\"389\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The secret to staying in place with an anchor (or one of the secrets — there are many) is to give it some slack, referred to as \"scope.\" </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Letting out line in a ratio of 5 feet to every 1 foot of water depth will provide a secure hold on the bottom and keep you in one place. It may sound counterintuitive, but letting out even more line makes the anchor hold even stronger. In conditions of heavy wind or chop, a ratio of 8:1 may be needed to keep you safe and secure.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My father and I don’t fish as often as we used to. The little aluminum rowboat sits behind the garage, the mushroom anchor still resting in the bottom of the bow, attached to the same frayed and spliced length of yellow nylon rope. Still, now that I finally know how an anchor works, I’m less concerned with the distance between the boat and the anchor, and more concerned with the distance between the anchor and me. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->','How to Use an Anchor','','publish','open','open','','how-to-use-an-anchor','','','2019-11-14 22:17:44','2019-11-14 22:17:44','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?p=935',0,'post','',0),(1574,8,'2019-12-03 22:06:29','2019-12-03 22:06:29','','The Cashmere Cap of Courage','','publish','closed','closed','','the-cashmere-cap-of-courage','','','2019-12-03 22:06:29','2019-12-03 22:06:29','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?post_type=product&#038;p=1574',0,'product','',0),(1575,8,'2019-12-03 22:06:26','2019-12-03 22:06:26','','Cashmere CoC','','inherit','open','closed','','cashmere-coc','','','2019-12-03 22:06:26','2019-12-03 22:06:26','',1574,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Cashmere-CoC.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(939,8,'2019-11-12 20:23:45','2019-11-12 20:23:45','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Fall is a time for harvest, not only in the garden or field but in the woods as well. Collecting wild mushrooms can be a daunting task for beginners, so it’s best to start off simple —&nbsp;all you\'ll need to get going is a basket for safe transport, and a <a href=\"https://www.bestmadeco.com/products/multipurpose-mushroom-knife\">mushroom knife</a> or digging tool. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here’s a crash course on four unmistakable and delicious mushrooms you can find in the forest — and one mushroom you should know to avoid.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":30} -->\n<div style=\"height:30px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<h3 style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>Chanterelles, <em>Cantharellus cibarius</em></strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1192,\"align\":\"center\",\"width\":675,\"height\":450} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter is-resized\"><img src=\"http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Chanterelles-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1192\" width=\"675\" height=\"450\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The chanterelle is the state mushroom of Oregon (one of only two states to have an official fungus), and is universally popular.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Easily identifiable and widespread, the chanterelle is a great mushroom to build your foraging confidence with. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"left\"} -->\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><strong>COLOR</strong>: The bright yellow-orange skin is eye-catching and a good distinguishing feature; the color should be consistent throughout.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"left\"} -->\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><strong>SHAPE</strong>: The caps will be convex when young and will turn upwards into a funnel shape with age. Looking under the caps, you’ll find the clearest characteristic: instead of typical mushroom “gills,” chanterelles have thicker “veins” that fork irregularly at the ends. The “veins” are also described as “decurrent,” which means they run down the stem.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>HABITAT</strong>: Chanterelles are found in mixed-conifer forests throughout the fall.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The smell should be pleasant and mild, with a hint of apricot.&nbsp;When you’re cooking your haul, simmer the mushrooms in water first to reduce their natural moisture, then fry up for a meaty, flavorful addition to a roasted vegetable dish.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":30} -->\n<div style=\"height:30px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<h3 style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>Lobster mushroom, <em>Russula brevipes </em>and<em> Hypomyces lactifluorum</em></strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1194,\"align\":\"center\",\"width\":675,\"height\":450} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter is-resized\"><img src=\"http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Lobster-Mushroom.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1194\" width=\"675\" height=\"450\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Identifying a lobster mushroom is a two-for-one deal because what is known as the lobster mushroom is actually a relationship between two fungi. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Russula brevipes</em> is a distinct but bland member of the Russula family, which is edible in its own right, but becomes a delicacy when parasitized by another fungus, <em>Hypomyces lactifluorum</em>. “Parasitized” is not the first word that brings “delicious” to mind, but <em>Hypomyces</em> transforms an otherwise boring <em>Russula</em> (and a few other species) into a vibrant, choice mushroom famous for its fishy flavor.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>COLOR</strong>:<br><strong><em>Russula brevipes</em></strong> is white to pale brown. <br><strong><em>Hypomyces lactifluorum</em></strong> is a bright reddish-orange. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>SHAPE</strong><br><strong><em>Russula brevipes</em></strong> is large, with a cap that is wider than the stem is tall. Gills and stem break cleanly like chalk. The veil is absent.&nbsp;<br><strong><em>Hypomyces lactifluorum</em> </strong>has<strong> </strong>smoothed-out features. The host is reshaped into a cup or funnel shape, resembling a chanterelle that has been plastered over. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>HABITAT</strong>: Look around conifers, especially fir, Douglas fir, and hemlock.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you find <em>Russula brevipes</em>, feel free to collect it and see if you care for its flavor (after sauteing in butter and garlic, of course) — or you can use it as a guide to spotting nearby lobster mushrooms. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":30} -->\n<div style=\"height:30px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<h3 style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>Shaggy Mane, <em>Coprinus comatus</em></strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1197,\"align\":\"center\",\"width\":675,\"height\":450} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter is-resized\"><img src=\"http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Shaggy-Mane.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1197\" width=\"675\" height=\"450\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Shaggy mane is another great “starter” mushroom, as it is hard to miss and hard to get wrong.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>COLOR: </strong>White with a pale brown center. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>SHAPE: </strong>The tall, columnar, shaggy cap can be spotted from a distance. Often grows in clusters.&nbsp;Cap has ragged, \"shaggy\" scales along the surface with a shingled appearance. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>HABITAT: </strong>Widespread, even in urban areas</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Coprinus</em> is an urgent reminder to get going while the picking’s good: a member of the “Inky Cap” family, <em>Coprinus</em> will degrade into a dripping, black mess once it is past maturity. This makes the edibility easy to identify — if it looks like it could be found in a grocery store, it’s in perfect condition, and if any part has started to ooze black, it should be left alone. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":30} -->\n<div style=\"height:30px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<h3 style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>Hedgehog, <em>Hydnum repandum, H. umbilicatum</em></strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1193,\"align\":\"center\",\"width\":675,\"height\":450} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter is-resized\"><img src=\"http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Hedgehog.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1193\" width=\"675\" height=\"450\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Hedgehog mushroom is a great find when on a chanterelle hunt — its similar color will catch the eye of the mushroom hunter.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>COLOR:</strong> Creamy orange to light brown. </li><li><strong>SHAPE</strong>: The “dentate” underside of the cap resembles a cluster of tiny stalactites, which are easily broken off. It\'s quite large, with a fairly thick and eccentric stem (not attached at the center of the cap). The irregular cap may form a broad indent at the center. </li><li><strong>HABITAT</strong>: Found in mixed-conifer forests throughout the fall. </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you find a mushroom matching this description but it has a scaly, shingled appearance, it\'s a different species: <em>H. umbilicatum</em>. It\'s similar in color but has a central stem and a distinct indent at the top center of the cap —&nbsp;both are edible and delicious. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you find a mushroom matching this description but it has a scaly, shingled appearance, it is a different species (<em>H. imbricatum</em>), which isn\'t poisonous but isn’t very tasty, either. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":30} -->\n<div style=\"height:30px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<h3 style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>Death Cap, <em>Amanita phalloides</em></strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1191,\"align\":\"center\",\"width\":675,\"height\":450} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter is-resized\"><img src=\"http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Amanita-Mushroom.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1191\" width=\"675\" height=\"450\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While <em>Amanita phalloides</em> is more common in Europe than in North America, it\'s still fairly widespread. This mushroom isn\'t edible, but it is one that should be known by all — it\'s particularly dangerous. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Amanita family is often regarded as a “more harm than good” family — while there are a few edibles in the group, it contains some of the most worrisome toxic mushrooms. It’s best to not risk your health on positive identification. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Amanita family is distinguished by the “<strong>universal veil</strong>,” often accompanied by a “<strong>partial veil</strong>” or “<strong>annulus</strong>.”&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Universal veils</strong> can be thin and cottony to thick and egg-like; they entirely envelop the young mushroom, and as the mushroom grows, it eventually bursts through the veil. Remnants of the veil can be found at the base of the mushroom or stuck to parts of the cap — the Amanitas often have thick, vase-like veils at their base. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <strong>partial veil</strong>, or <strong>annulus</strong>, covers the young gills until they mature. When the cap spreads open, the veil tears and can leave a distinct ring around the upper stalk of the mushroom, looking like a type of collar. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Amanita phalloides</em> has a thick, persistent universal veil (called a volva), generally has a greenish tint to the pale-brown cap, a skirt-like annulus, and whitish gills that are sometimes slightly green.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If a mushroom looks like it is emerging from a sack, or has a distinct annulus, it is best for the beginner naturalist to stay away. This family is the one most responsible for mushroom poisoning, but knowledge of the dangerous varieties will only instill confidence that the wild mushrooms you <em>do</em> pick are nothing but delicious and healthful.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<h3 style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>The Safety Talk</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Only attempt to eat a mushroom if you have 100% confidence in a positive identification! Even then, it is best to eat wild mushrooms you haven’t tried before in small doses. Some folks can experience gastrointestinal upset even with the common edible mushrooms, so cook up a small piece to taste, and see how you feel.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Only pick fresh specimens — if there are signs of drying or decay, leave the mushrooms and let them proliferate. Poisonous mushrooms cannot harm you just by handling them, and it is extremely rare that a mushroom is toxic enough to do any damage when only a small bite is ingested. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The best way to learn is to start collecting and identifying in the woods around you. Take it slow, and don’t cook anything until you\'re positive it\'s safe to eat. Photos are the most helpful resource in confirming an ID, and there are myriad resources for photo identifications provided by fellow amateur mycologists. There’s nothing quite like the thrill of finding choice edibles on a hike — after your first plate of wild-harvested, sauteed chanterelles, there’s no going back. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>  <strong>Extra Block :</strong> Only pick fresh specimens </li><li> Poisonous mushrooms cannot harm you just by handling them, and it is extremely rare that a mushroom is toxic enough to do any damage when only a small bite is ingested. </li><li> The best way to learn is to start collecting and identifying in the woods around you. <ul><li>  Only pick fresh specimens </li><li> Poisonous mushrooms cannot harm you just by handling them, and it is extremely rare that a mushroom is toxic enough to do any damage when only a small bite is ingested. </li><li> The best way to learn is to start collecting and identifying in the woods around you.    </li></ul></li><li> The best way to learn is to start collecting and identifying in the woods around you.   </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','5 Fall Mushrooms: A Beginner’s Guide','','publish','open','open','','5-fall-mushrooms-beginners-guide','','','2019-12-11 14:16:12','2019-12-11 14:16:12','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?p=939',0,'post','',0),(1275,7,'2019-11-14 19:30:54','2019-11-14 19:30:54','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I often heard the phrase “Come over here and let me show you how an anchor works,” from my father as we sat fishing in the little aluminum rowboat that used to be Uncle Stan’s. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It was his usual response when I would question the size of the fish he’d just caught or challenge the \"truthiness\" of one of his many stories. He always said it jokingly, implying that he would like to throw me overboard. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Still, it made me wonder exactly what <em>was</em> happening down there, as I watched our little mushroom anchor disappear into the murky lake water.&nbsp;I imagined the anchor dropping straight down to the lake bottom, with its weight holding us securely in place —&nbsp;but when I would go fishing by myself, drop the anchor, and expect it to work, I always found myself drifting.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1200,\"align\":\"center\",\"width\":768,\"height\":389} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter is-resized\"><img src=\"http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Anchor-Illustration-1024x518.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1200\" width=\"768\" height=\"389\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The secret to staying in place with an anchor (or one of the secrets — there are many) is to give it some slack, referred to as \"scope.\" </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Letting out line in a ratio of 5 feet to every 1 foot of water depth will provide a secure hold on the bottom and keep you in one place. It may sound counterintuitive, but letting out even more line makes the anchor hold even stronger. In conditions of heavy wind or chop, a ratio of 8:1 may be needed to keep you safe and secure.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My father and I don’t fish as often as we used to. The little aluminum rowboat sits behind the garage, the mushroom anchor still resting in the bottom of the bow, attached to the same frayed and spliced length of yellow nylon rope. Still, now that I finally know how an anchor works, I’m less concerned with the distance between the boat and the anchor, and more concerned with the distance between the anchor and me. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->','How to Use an Anchor','','inherit','closed','closed','','935-autosave-v1','','','2019-11-14 19:30:54','2019-11-14 19:30:54','',935,'https://editorial.bestmadeco.com/uncategorized/935-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(894,8,'2019-11-07 17:48:32','2019-11-07 17:48:32','','Juniper','','inherit','open','closed','','juniper','','','2019-11-07 17: