//editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/HudsonBayAxe.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1104,8,'2019-11-13 23:00:01','2019-11-13 23:00:01','','The American Felling Axe','','publish','closed','closed','','the-american-felling-axe','','','2019-11-13 23:00:01','2019-11-13 23:00:01','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?post_type=product&#038;p=1104',0,'product','',0),(1730,8,'2020-01-17 19:34:47','2020-01-17 19:34:47','<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our <a href=\"https://www.bestmadeco.com/collections/denim\">denim</a> is produced in small batches and slow-woven on vintage shuttle looms at Japan’s premier mill, where the ring-spun yarn is dyed with 100% pure indigo, then singed and sanforized for the perfect texture and fit. Wherever it’s from, exceptional denim deserves to be taken care of. We’ve rounded up a few tips that will keep it looking its best. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator {\"className\":\"is-style-default\"} -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator is-style-default\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<h3 style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>DENIM CARE TIPS</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":30} -->\n<div style=\"height:30px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Generally speaking, <a href=\"https://www.bestmadeco.com/collections/denim\">pure denim</a> (denim without elastane mixed in for stretch) should be washed as infrequently as possible. Washing, and especially drying, causes fading and weakens the cotton fibers —&nbsp;in other words, your nice new denim won’t develop creasing as well, and will be more likely to blow out.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So, how do you best care for denim between washing — and what do you do when the time comes?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":25} -->\n<div style=\"height:25px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>If you get a small stain, <strong>try spot cleaning</strong>. You can try scrubbing at stains with a toothbrush, water, and a gentle detergent —&nbsp;always spot test behind a pocket first, though.<br><br></li><li>You can <strong>try freezing your denim</strong> to help kill any bacteria and tackle odors. Just put your favorite pair in an airtight bag before sticking it in the freezer for 24 hours. <br><br></li><li>In the same vein, <strong>if you get gum on your jeans, don’t despair</strong>. Go ahead and freeze them as described above, and then scrape the gum off with the edge of a fine blade; when you’ve removed as much of it as you can, you can wash as usual. <br><br></li><li>If something must be washed, you can also <strong>try handwashing first</strong>. Just make sure to use <em>cold</em> water only, and always line dry.&nbsp;</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":30} -->\n<div style=\"height:30px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Though you want to wash your denim as little as possible, as dirt and grime start to build up they can actually make the fabric more brittle and increase the likelihood of holes and rips. Plus, sooner or later, your garments are bound to smell. When the time comes to clean your j<a href=\"https://www.bestmadeco.com/collections/denim\">eans or jackets</a>, there are three key points to keep in mind — and a good <a href=\"https://www.bestmadeco.com/products/denim-wash\">Denim Wash</a> doesn’t hurt, either.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":55} -->\n<div style=\"height:55px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<h3 style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>HOW TO WASH YOUR DENIM</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":35} -->\n<div style=\"height:35px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Remember, raw denim and new denim should always be washed separately, to avoid the indigo bleeding onto other garments.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>Before washing, examine your denim for any stains and pre-treat them. If there’s a particularly smelly section, apply a little plain white vinegar and work it into the fabric, before presoaking the whole piece in room temperature water with a little more vinegar. <br><br></li><li>When it’s ready to pop in the washing machine, <strong>turn your denim inside out</strong>. This helps to prevent abrasion and fading. If you have one, you can also put your denim inside a mesh laundry bag to protect the hardware and any special detailing. <br><br></li><li>Add the appropriate amount of <a href=\"https://www.bestmadeco.com/products/denim-wash\">Denim Wash</a> (or any other mild detergent) to your detergent drawer, and then set the machine to the normal cycle. <em>Always</em> <strong>make sure you use cold water<em> </em></strong>for all non-white denim. <br><br></li><li>Never put denim in the dryer — <strong>always hang to dry or line dry</strong>. It prevents fading, shrinking, and extra abrasion.&nbsp;</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Truly great denim is hard to come by. Once you manage to find <a href=\"https://www.bestmadeco.com/collections/denim\">the perfect pair of jeans</a> — the right wash, a comfortable fit, just-so details — do yourself a favor, and learn how to take care of them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":50} -->\n<div style=\"height:50px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->','How-To: Denim Care','','publish','open','open','','how-to-denim-care','','','2020-01-17 19:35:27','2020-01-17 19:35:27','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?p=1730',0,'post','',0),(1731,8,'2020-01-17 17:47:46','2020-01-17 17:47:46','','Denim Wash','','publish','closed','closed','','denim-wash','','','2020-01-17 17:47:46','2020-01-17 17:47:46','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?post_type=product&#038;p=1731',0,'product','',0),(1732,8,'2020-01-17 17:47:41','2020-01-17 17:47:41','','Denim Wash','','inherit','open','closed','','denim-wash','','','2020-01-17 17:47:41','2020-01-17 17:47:41','',1731,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Denim-Wash.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1733,8,'2020-01-17 17:48:46','2020-01-17 17:48:46','','Best Made Raw Selvedge Jeans','','publish','closed','closed','','best-made-raw-selvedge-jeans','','','2020-01-17 17:48:46','2020-01-17 17:48:46','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?post_type=product&#038;p=1733',0,'product','',0),(1734,8,'2020-01-17 17:48:42','2020-01-17 17:48:42','','Raw Denim','','inherit','open','closed','','raw-denim','','','2020-01-17 17:48:42','2020-01-17 17:48:42','',1733,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Raw-Denim.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1735,8,'2020-01-17 17:49:20','2020-01-17 17:49:20','','Best Made Rinsed Selvedge Jeans','','publish','closed','closed','','best-made-rinsed-selvedge-jeans','','','2020-01-17 17:49:20','2020-01-17 17:49:20','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?post_type=product&#038;p=1735',0,'product','',0),(1736,8,'2020-01-17 17:49:16','2020-01-17 17:49:16','','Rinsed Denim','','inherit','open','closed','','rinsed-denim','','','2020-01-17 17:49:16','2020-01-17 17:49:16','',1735,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Rinsed-Denim.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1737,8,'2020-01-17 17:49:50','2020-01-17 17:49:50','','The Best Made Denim Jacket','','publish','closed','closed','','the-best-made-denim-jacket','','','2020-01-17 17:49:50','2020-01-17 17:49:50','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?post_type=product&#038;p=1737',0,'product','',0),(1738,8,'2020-01-17 17:49:44','2020-01-17 17:49:44','','Denim Jacket','','inherit','open','closed','','denim-jacket','','','2020-01-17 17:49:44','2020-01-17 17:49:44','',1737,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Denim-Jacket.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1739,8,'2020-01-17 19:34:17','2020-01-17 19:34:17','','Denim Care Thumbnail','','inherit','open','closed','','denim-care-thumbnail','','','2020-01-17 19:34:17','2020-01-17 19:34:17','',1730,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Denim-Care-Thumbnail.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1740,8,'2020-01-17 19:34:26','2020-01-17 19:34:26','','Denim Care Feature','','inherit','open','closed','','denim-care-feature','','','2020-01-17 19:34:26','2020-01-17 19:34:26','',1730,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Denim-Care-Feature.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1743,8,'2020-01-22 19:56:26','2020-01-22 19:56:26','<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wool outclasses and outperforms most technical fabrics: it’s temperature-regulating and naturally odor-, stain-, and fire-resistant. For <a href=\"https://bestmadeco.com/clothing/sweaters\">sweaters</a>, <a href=\"https://bestmadeco.com/products/kersey-ranch-coat?taxon_id=1459\">coats</a>, <a href=\"https://bestmadeco.com/accessories/hats-headwear\">hats</a>, <a href=\"https://bestmadeco.com/camp-home/home/blankets\">blankets</a>, and <a href=\"https://bestmadeco.com/products/famous-red-wool-pullover?taxon_id=1459\">more</a> it’s one of our favorite materials — which is why we’re serious about keeping it looking (and working) its best. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator {\"className\":\"is-style-default\"} -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator is-style-default\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<h3 style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>WOOL CARE TIPS</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":30} -->\n<div style=\"height:30px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cashmere, merino, lambswool — whatever the knit, eventually it will start to get baggy, or pill, or develop loose threads or pulls. Thankfully, most of those issues are fairly easy to address. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":25} -->\n<div style=\"height:25px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li><strong>For pilling, your best bet is a </strong><a href=\"https://bestmadeco.com/products/sweater-stone\"><strong>sweater stone</strong></a><strong>.</strong> Lay your garment flat on top of a pillow or something soft (it provides grip) and then slide the stone in one direction with short, gentle strokes. Shake out the garment when you’re done. <br><br></li><li>Never cut loose threads; the yarn might unravel. Instead, gently pull the surrounding area to try and work the threads back into shape, and then <strong>use a needle or safety pin to pull the yarn through to the inside</strong> of the garment. <br><br></li><li>Sweaters are quick to bag and lose their shape. <strong>Never hang your knits</strong>, or leave anything in them — they should always be folded and laid flat. <br><br></li><li><strong>With small stains, a spot treatment is best</strong>. Rinse the stain out with cold water, and then blot dry with a clean cloth.<br><br></li><li>There are <strong>a few things to keep in mind for storage</strong>: air things out every now and then, don’t vacuum pack anything, and — if you can — store them laid flat in a linen garment bag or drawer (longterm, plastic can degrade wool fibers).</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":35} -->\n<div style=\"height:35px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of the main concerns with wool is the dreaded moth hole; bugs love to eat wool because of the protein in it. Luckily, there’s a natural solution: <strong>aromatic red cedar</strong>. Purchase drawer liners or wooden blocks and store them with your garments to help keep insects at bay. <br><br>Should your cedar ever lose its potency, you can also purchase <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Giles-Kendall-Cedar-Restores-Original/dp/B002RXHME0/ref=sr_1_1_sspa?keywords=cedar+oil&amp;qid=1579210385&amp;sr=8-1-spons&amp;psc=1&amp;smid=ATZ61JQHZC6XB&amp;spLa=ZW5jcnlwdGVkUXVhbGlmaWVyPUFNN1hQQTQ4OTFUMzUmZW5jcnlwdGVkSWQ9QTA2NTExNDMzUUswNUZUN1VBWUYzJmVuY3J5cHRlZEFkSWQ9QTAxMDY1ODgxUDVZM0VGT0tCUUlYJndpZGdldE5hbWU9c3BfYXRmJmFjdGlvbj1jbGlja1JlZGlyZWN0JmRvTm90TG9nQ2xpY2s9dHJ1ZQ==\">cedar oil</a> to help renew the wood — sand your block, wipe it clean, and apply the oil in thin, light coats with an old rag. Wipe off the excess and place the plank in a dry place for two weeks. Give it a final wipe with a damp cloth, and you’re good to go. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":55} -->\n<div style=\"height:55px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<h3 style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>HOW TO WASH YOUR WOOL</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>How often you need to wash your wool depends heavily on the particular garment. Bulky knit sweaters or thick blankets? Very rarely. The merino baselayers you live in all winter? More often. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.thelaundress.com/clean-talk-blog/clean-and-preserve-precious-wool-cashmere-at-home.html\">Handwashing</a> is almost always the best approach, though <a href=\"https://bestmadeco.com/accessories/socks-underwear\">baselayers and socks</a> can tolerate the washing machine (on the delicate or woolen cycle, ideally in a mesh bag). When the time to wash comes, just follow these steps for success. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":25} -->\n<div style=\"height:25px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>Fill a sink, tub, or bin with cold water — <strong><em>always</em> use cold water with knits</strong>. <br><br></li><li>Add the detergent, per product instructions, and thoroughly mix it into the water. <strong>We like a dedicated <a href=\"https://bestmadeco.com/products/wool-cashmere-shampoo\">Wool &amp; Cashmere Shampoo</a></strong>. Standard detergents contain enzymes that eat away at the protein in wool, which is a big part of what causes shrinkage and holes, so make sure to use a gentle, pH-neutral wash. <br><br></li><li>Turn your garment inside out, and lay it in the bath. Let it soak, fully immersed, for a few minutes. <strong>Gently squeeze it</strong> in the water to work in the detergent. <br><br></li><li>Finish with a cold rinse in clean water to remove any detergent in the fibers. Lightly wring out or press out your cleaned garment — avoid over twisting, which can weaken the wool. <br><br></li><li>If you want them to keep their shape and size, never put knits in the dryer, and don’t hang dry them either. Instead, <strong>always lay flat to dry</strong> — you can drape them over something or lay them out on a towel until they’re completely dry. </li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We favor wool over any of the synthetic alternatives — there’s really nothing better. Take care of it right, and it’ll last you a lifetime. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":50} -->\n<div style=\"height:50px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->','How-To: Wool Care','','publish','open','open','','how-to-wool-care','','','2020-01-22 19:56:27','2020-01-22 19:56:27','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?p=1743',0,'post','',0),(1391,8,'2019-11-14 22:48:30','2019-11-14 22:48:30','','Best Camping Axes Feature','','inherit','open','closed','','best-camping-axes-feature','','','2019-11-14 22:48:30','2019-11-14 22:48:30','',818,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Best-Camping-Axes-Feature.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1394,8,'2019-11-14 22:53:31','2019-11-14 22:53:31','','Best-Axes-Estwing','','inherit','open','closed','','best-axes-estwing','','','2019-11-14 22:53:31','2019-11-14 22:53:31','',818,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Best-Axes-Estwing.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1395,8,'2019-11-14 22:55:56','2019-11-14 22:55:56','','Best Axes Council Tool','','inherit','open','closed','','best-axes-council-tool','','','2019-11-14 22:55:56','2019-11-14 22:55:56','',818,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Best-Axes-Council-Tool.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1396,8,'2019-11-14 22:56:31','2019-11-14 22:56:31','','Best-Axes-Hudson','','inherit','open','closed','','best-axes-hudson','','','2019-11-14 22:56:31','2019-11-14 22:56:31','',818,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Best-Axes-Hudson.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1397,8,'2019-11-14 22:57:17','2019-11-14 22:57:17','','Best-Axes-SOG','','inherit','open','closed','','best-axes-sog','','','2019-11-14 22:57:17','2019-11-14 22:57:17','',818,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Best-Axes-SOG.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1398,8,'2019-11-14 22:57:40','2019-11-14 22:57:40','','Best-Axes-Hatchet','','inherit','open','closed','','best-axes-hatchet','','','2019-11-14 22:57:40','2019-11-14 22:57:40','',818,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Best-Axes-Hatchet.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1751,8,'2020-01-24 16:49:58','2020-01-24 16:49:58','<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":50} -->\n<div style=\"height:50px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In their second collaboration together, Standards Manual and photographer Brian Kelley have released <em><a href=\"https://bestmadeco.com/products/parks\">Parks</a></em>, a collection of 300+ United States national park maps, ephemera, and brochures. Showcasing nearly a century of art and cartography, it provides a compelling visual history of America’s parkland. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We recently sat down with Kelley and Standards Manual founders, designers Jesse Reed and Hamish Smyth, to talk about the process of creating the book. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":20} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":25} -->\n<div style=\"height:25px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><em>BEST MADE CO.: </em>Where did the original idea for <em>Parks </em>come from?</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>BRIAN KELLEY:</em> I had met up with Jesse for coffee one morning shortly after the release of <em>Objects</em>, our first collaborative project, and we were brainstorming on what we could do next.  We both thought the idea of National Park Maps could be interesting…So I started searching the dark web of eBay. A few months later I shared my initial findings and Jesse and Hamish were really hyped on what I was digging up. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":25} -->\n<div style=\"height:25px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1754,\"align\":\"center\",\"width\":675,\"height\":450} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter is-resized\"><img src=\"https://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/PARKS-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1754\" width=\"675\" height=\"450\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":25} -->\n<div style=\"height:25px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><em>BMC: </em>Is the entire collection presented here — and if not, how did you decide which pieces to include?   </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>STANDARDS MANUAL:</em> No. Brian has a massive collection, and because of our limited resources as an independent publisher, we had to be semi-selective with what we included in the book. We wanted to display a wide range of materials — both from a visual and content perspective — capturing the essence of each decade in Brian’s collection. There are pieces that we don’t personally think are aesthetically “good,\" but who are we to say what’s good or not? There’s enough diversity to choose from and have the reader make those conclusions on their own. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":25} -->\n<div style=\"height:25px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1760,\"align\":\"center\",\"width\":675,\"height\":450} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter is-resized\"><img src=\"https://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/PARKS-3.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1760\" width=\"675\" height=\"450\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":25} -->\n<div style=\"height:25px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><em>BMC: </em>Was there a particular goal you had for <em>Parks</em>? </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>BK</em>: For myself, it was to represent the collection of maps to the best ability, not only showing the amazing design and taste of the 60s and 70s but even the worst of it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>SM</em>: Our mission as a publisher is to preserve graphic design history. The maps and brochures found in this book have been lightly, if ever, included in the historical canon of our profession (Vignelli’s Unigrid, as the exception here). Further to that, the design credit is almost entirely absent from all of this work, which is unfortunate. We hope that by exposing the collection we’ll be able to give credit to the (presumably) dozens or hundreds of designers who created these incredible materials. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><em>BMC: </em>What was the photography process like? </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>BK</em>: Every cover of the map is a scan at extremely high resolution. Hamish and Jesse then went through the collection and picked out details that they saw as important. After we had those selects I shot photographs of those details.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>SM</em>: Each new map or brochure that Brian would find was a surprise to us. He would text over a new lot of maps, and we would freak out (that we’ve never seen it before, and that we’re going to be able to share it for the first time to most people).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":25} -->\n<div style=\"height:25px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1759,\"align\":\"center\",\"width\":675,\"height\":450} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter is-resized\"><img src=\"https://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/PARKS-2.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1759\" width=\"675\" height=\"450\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":25} -->\n<div style=\"height:25px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><em>BMC: </em>How do you think the anonymity of these works impacts how viewers receive them?</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>SM</em>: I wonder if people consciously think about that aspect of it. Truthfully, not too many people have asked about design credits, which is an interesting observation about the expectation of design in our environment — questioning who designed what by the general public is low on the conversation list. The designers should get credit, of course, but if you knew who did it, would it affect how you appreciate the work? A good question for readers. Most public or government work is rarely credited, even today, so it’s not so different — the only difference is we have blogs and portfolio sites that make finding that information much easier than in 1966.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><em>BMC: </em>Do you have a favorite piece in the collection? </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>BK</em>: My favorite piece is the 1934 Proposed Olympic National Park brochure. This might be my favorite park brochure I\'ve collected. The amount of information inside is immense. Also, super relevant to the current situation in the Tongass and other parks in the U.S.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>SM</em>: Jesse speaking here, but my favorite is the “danger” brochure from 1971. An obvious inspiration for the cover — talk about impact!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><em>BMC: </em>What about the U.S. National Parks speaks to you? </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>BK</em>: For myself…we\'re incredibly fortunate to have the National Parks in the U.S. There are countries that don’t have national parks, and sometimes they have to rely on private landowners having the vision to see past greed and financial profit from natural resources. Certain parks give us a brief view back into the past and what was…before we had such severe shifts in the baseline of how we perceive the natural world today.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>SM</em>: Visiting the national parks, particularly during the era of the maps in this book, is rather romantic. I like to think of a time where you got in a car, grabbed a road map, pulled up to a national park, were handed another map, and went on to have a true adventure. There were no user reviews or Google images, everything was unexpected and new (to you, at least). Technology can be great, but it takes away some of the romanticism of the unknown — that’s what national parks conjures up for us.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":35} -->\n<div style=\"height:35px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[1757,1758],\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-gallery aligncenter columns-2 is-cropped\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/PARKS-Cover.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1757\" data-link=\"https://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?attachment_id=1757\" class=\"wp-image-1757\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/PARKS-Interior-3.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1758\" data-link=\"https://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?attachment_id=1758\" class=\"wp-image-1758\"/></figure></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":35} -->\n<div style=\"height:35px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><em>BM: </em>How does the park design seen today reflect the current cultural or historical moment?</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>SM</em>: Nothing would make us happier to see the resurgence of an accurately implemented Vignelli Unigrid system — Helvetica and all! This happens all the time, unfortunately. The NASA design story follows a similar trajectory. Graphic design isn’t the problem. It’s the lack of Federal funding and authority when it comes to protecting and preserving these precious pieces of land. Anything that we (as designers) can do to help inform and help grow the appreciation of national parks is worth the effort. This book is a part of that effort. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":35} -->\n<div style=\"height:35px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[1755,1756],\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-gallery aligncenter columns-2 is-cropped\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/PARKS-Interior-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1755\" data-link=\"https://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?attachment_id=1755\" class=\"wp-image-1755\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/PARKS-Interior-2.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1756\" data-link=\"https://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?attachment_id=1756\" class=\"wp-image-1756\"/></figure></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":35} -->\n<div style=\"height:35px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><em>BMC: </em>Why do you think ephemera like this is able to so powerfully connect us to a specific place and time?  </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>BK</em>: It allows the viewer to have a connection to the past and have a certain feeling that they know they can’t get today. The same way people romanticize over vintage photos of NYC and Paris. What’s interesting is when you’re able to have the ability to see that the present you live in is already the past and certain things...photographs, ticket stubs, newspapers, are already part of a larger collection. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>SM:</em> We second what Brian said, and would also add that a collection like this serves a great debt to the history books of visual communication, specifically in the United States. Everything from printing technology, typographic development, and cultural observations of each decade’s time are all included in the depths of this work. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":40} -->\n<div style=\"height:40px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em><a href=\"https://bestmadeco.com/products/parks\">Parks</a></em> is available for purchase online and in our New York store at 36 White Street, (646) 478-7092.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":50} -->\n<div style=\"height:50px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->','The Making of PARKS','','publish','open','open','','making-parks','','','2020-01-24 16:50:00','2020-01-24 16:50:00','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/?p=1751',0,'post','',0),(1389,7,'2019-11-14 22:44:33','2019-11-14 22:44:33','','Sam-McGee-Feature copy','','inherit','open','closed','','sam-mcgee-feature-copy','','','2019-11-14 22:44:33','2019-11-14 22:44:33','',478,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Sam-McGee-Feature-copy.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1254,8,'2019-11-14 19:10:33','2019-11-14 19:10:33','','Jared Feature','','inherit','open','closed','','jared-feature','','','2019-11-14 19:10:33','2019-11-14 19:10:33','',0,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Jared-Feature.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1255,8,'2019-11-14 19:10:35','2019-11-14 19:10:35','','Jared Thumbnail','','inherit','open','closed','','jared-thumbnail','','','2019-11-14 19:10:52','2019-11-14 19:10:52','',819,'http://editorial.bestmadeco.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Jared-Thumbnail.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1280,2,'2019-11-14 19:45:31','2019-11-14 19:45:31','a:10:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"text\";s:12:\"instructions\";s:0:\"\";s:8:\"required\";i:0;s:17:\"conditional_logic\";i:0;s:7:\"wrapper\";a:3:{s:5:\"width\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"class\";s:0:\"\";s:2:\"id\";s:0:\"\";}s:13:\"default_value\";s: